pull_request.body:
This commit introduces several major features and bug fixes to improve the bot's functionality and stability.

Features:
- **Smart Video Splitting:** Implements an intelligent video splitter that uses `ffmpeg` to create parts that are under Telegram's file size limit without re-encoding. Includes a rich UI for split file uploads.
- **Parallel Telegram Downloader:** Adds a high-speed parallel downloader for large files from Telegram, based on the rapidStream method, to significantly improve download speeds.

Bug Fixes:
- **ValueError in video processing:** Fixes a crash caused by an inconsistent return signature in the `process_video` function.
- **Message Flood:** Adds a safeguard to prevent `MESSAGE_NOT_MODIFIED` errors by checking if the status message content has changed before editing.
- **NameError in telegram_download:** Fixes a crash caused by a missing import of the `Config` object.

Your `param.yaml` file contains the path from the root of your Git repository to your CloudFormation template as well as the parameters and tags for your stack. When changes are committed to your repository, CloudFormation automatically updates the stack, its parameters, and tags. 

#### How do I update the `param.yaml` file?
Edit your `param.yaml` file and commit the changes to your repository. Make sure that you commit the changes to the path and branch in the repository that are specified in the deployment file.

# refactor: convert App folder from Flow to TypeScript ## Summary This PR converts the `src/components/App` folder from Flow to TypeScript as part of the ongoing migration effort in the `eh/feat/DHIS2-19350-refactor-flow-to-typescript` branch. **Files converted:** - `App.component.js` → `App.component.tsx` - Main App component with Redux Provider setup - `AppContents.component.js` → `AppContents.component.tsx` - App container with Material-UI styling - `index.js` → `index.ts` - Simple export barrel **Key changes:** - Removed Flow syntax (`// @flow`, exact object types `{| ... |}`) - Added TypeScript type definitions following project patterns - Applied Material-UI `withStyles` TypeScript pattern with `WithStyles` - Fixed import ordering to satisfy ESLint requirements - Used `any` type for Redux store prop (see notes below) ## Review & Testing Checklist for Human - [ ] **Start the app locally** (`yarn start`) and verify it renders without errors - most critical test - [ ] **Evaluate store typing approach**: I used `any` for the Redux store prop instead of the proper `ReduxStore` type due to a TypeScript error. Consider if this is acceptable or if the typing should be fixed properly. - [ ] **Verify Material-UI styling**: Check that the app container styling still works correctly after the TypeScript conversion **Recommended test plan:** 1. Run `yarn start` and access http://localhost:3000 2. Verify the app loads without console errors 3. Check that basic navigation and rendering works as expected --- ### Diagram ```mermaid %%{ init : { "theme" : "default" }}%% graph TD App["src/components/App/

issue.title: Sidebar folders order depends on their page order property
issue.body:
### What version of `starlight` are you using?

0.14.0

### What version of `astro` are you using?

3.6.4

### What package manager are you using?

pnpm

### What operating system are you using?

Mac

### What browser are you using?

Chrome

### Describe the Bug

As discussed on Discord,
```
Structure:
 - docs/
    - category/
      - folder-1/
        - page-1.md
        - page-2.md
      - folder-2/
        - page-1.md
        - page-2.md
```

If I give my folder-1/page-1.md an order property of 10, and my folder-2/page-1.md an order property of 5, I end-up with my folder-2 being ranked above folder-1 in my sidebar.

Said differently, autogenerated folders are sorted according to the order of the first page in the directory.

In the stackblitz example linked below, in the fruits directory, the banana subdirectory comes before the apples subdirectory because it has a page with order 1, when apples has a page with order 5.

### Link to Minimal Reproducible Example

https://stackblitz.com/edit/github-dssfwv?file=src%2Fcontent%2Fdocs%2Ffruits%2Fbananas%2Flatundan.md

### Participation

- [X] I am willing to submit a pull request for this issue.

comment.body:
> Nuxt Content has [a very nice way](https://content.nuxt.com/usage/content-directory#ordering) of supporting custom ordering, by allowing numeric prefixes in the filename, which it then ignores when generating the slug/ID.

Since Starlight [0.35.0](https://github.com/withastro/starlight/releases/tag/%40astrojs%2Fstarlight%400.35.0) added the [`generateId()`](https://starlight.astro.build/reference/configuration/#generateid) callback function which enables customization of how URLs from filenames (`entry`) are transformed, you can now achieve the same behavior in Starlight (but without i18n unfortunately).

I wrote a blog post of how to do exactly that if anyone is still interested in such a setup: https://blog.trueberryless.org/blog/starlight-autogenerate-whole-sidebar/
